The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Rome, Feb. 13: Fiat and General Motors (GM) have agreed that the US carmaker will not take up an option to buy Fiat?s auto business but forfeit $1.5 billion to the Italian company, ANSA news agency reported today. Fiat?s board approved the deal at an emergency meeting today. The two auto giants had been locked in a dispute over the option, contained in an alliance reached in 2000 and reviewed in 2003, under which Fiat could compel GM to buy its automotive division.

 New Delhi, Feb. 13: The global IT services market grew 6.7 per cent in 2004 to touch $607.8 billion from $569.6 billion in 2003. In 2004, the growth, adjusted to the decline in dollar value, was just 2.2 per cent, according to analyst firm Gartner. 

 New Delhi, Feb. 13: The Competition Commission of India (CCI) has kicked off efforts to identify major sectors where possible monopolies or cartels are in operation. A committee, headed by Vijay Kelkar, held its first meeting late last week to nail down monopolies in various sectors of the economy.

 New Delhi, Feb. 13: The government has sought clarifications from Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltd (BSNL) for alleged use of fixed wireless phones to provide mobile PCO facility in some parts of the country, and has asked the PSU to reply within seven days.

 Vijayawada, Feb. 13: Nine bank unions will go on a strike next month to protest against the reform policies of the Centre, National Organisation of Bank Workers president K. R. Ramakrishna Punja said today.




